<p>
  Readability is how easily a reader can understand your writing. It's not about writing "simply" — it's about writing <em>efficiently</em>: clear, direct, well-structured text that delivers ideas without friction. Readability scores quantify this so you can measure and improve it.
</p>

<h2>Why Readability Matters</h2>

<p>
  The web is brutal for attention. Studies show most people scan rather than read — they skim headlines, the first sentence of paragraphs, and bullet points. Dense walls of text lose readers immediately.
</p>

<p>
  Readable content benefits you in several ways:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Lower bounce rate:</strong> Readers stay on the page when they can follow the text without effort</li>
  <li><strong>Broader audience:</strong> Content written at grade 8 is accessible to ~80% of adults, not just specialists</li>
  <li><strong>Better conversion:</strong> Landing pages and emails with clearer copy convert better</li>
  <li><strong>Indirect SEO:</strong> More time-on-page and fewer bounces are positive user experience signals</li>
</ul>

<h2>The Most Common Readability Formulas</h2>

<h3>Flesch Reading Ease</h3>
<p>
  The most widely used readability metric. Scores range from 0 to 100 — higher is easier.
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>90–100:</strong> Very easy (5th grade). Conversational, simple.</li>
  <li><strong>70–80:</strong> Fairly easy (6th grade). Most consumer content.</li>
  <li><strong>60–70:</strong> Standard (7th grade). Most blog posts and news articles.</li>
  <li><strong>50–60:</strong> Fairly difficult (10th–12th grade). Technical topics.</li>
  <li><strong>30–50:</strong> Difficult (college level). Academic papers.</li>
  <li><strong>0–30:</strong> Very difficult. Legal and scientific texts.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Flesch-Kincaid Grade Level</h3>
<p>
  Translates readability into a US school grade level. A score of 8.0 means an 8th grader can understand it. Most major newspapers target grade 8. Most web content should target grade 6–8.
</p>

<h3>Gunning Fog Index</h3>
<p>
  Estimates the years of formal education required to read text on first pass. Focus is on polysyllabic words (3+ syllables). A score of 12 = US high school graduation level. Target: below 12 for general content.
</p>

<h3>SMOG Index</h3>
<p>
  Similar to Gunning Fog but considered more accurate for health communication. Counts words with 3+ syllables. Used extensively in health and patient education materials.
</p>

