<h2>How to Improve Readability</h2>

<h3>1. Shorten your sentences</h3>
<p>
  Long sentences are the single biggest readability killer. Aim for an average sentence length of 15–20 words. If a sentence exceeds 30 words, split it.
</p>

<h3>2. Use simple words</h3>
<p>
  Replace polysyllabic words with simpler alternatives. Readability formulas penalise words with 3+ syllables because they slow readers down.
</p>
<ul>
  <li>"utilise" → "use"</li>
  <li>"demonstrate" → "show"</li>
  <li>"approximately" → "about"</li>
  <li>"facilitate" → "help"</li>
  <li>"terminate" → "end"</li>
</ul>

<h3>3. Use active voice</h3>
<p>
  Passive voice adds words and makes sentences harder to follow. "The report was written by the team" → "The team wrote the report."
</p>

<h3>4. Break up paragraphs</h3>
<p>
  Short paragraphs (3–4 sentences max) are easier to scan. Long paragraphs feel dense and invite skipping. Use subheadings to signal topic changes.
</p>

<h3>5. Use lists for parallel items</h3>
<p>
  When you have 3+ parallel items, a bullet list is almost always more readable than a sentence listing them with commas.
</p>

<h2>Readability Targets by Content Type</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>General blog posts:</strong> Flesch 60–70, Grade 7–8</li>
  <li><strong>News articles:</strong> Flesch 60–65, Grade 8</li>
  <li><strong>Email newsletters:</strong> Flesch 65–75, Grade 6–7</li>
  <li><strong>Technical documentation:</strong> Flesch 40–60, Grade 10–12 (some complexity unavoidable)</li>
  <li><strong>Health information:</strong> Flesch 70+, Grade 6 or below</li>
  <li><strong>Academic papers:</strong> Flesch 20–40, Grade 14–16</li>
</ul>

